segments.text: I want to start the first chapter of the book with your early childhood.

I have the letters that you wrote to me, which talk about a lot of your first impressions, which you remember, I think, sending me those, the ones about seeing the first time you saw a dead man, which is a very well-written piece.
You remember that one?
Yes, I do.
Do you know one?
Uh-huh.
That was Tom Ruby.
Uh-huh.
And when Roy was talking about the old Culberson place, and I told you about the chimney.
Yes, the chimney, right.
That is the old Culberson place.
It is.
That's exactly right.
Okay, that gives me a definition.
That gives you a definition of exactly.
Well, that was it.
I'm going to send you, I'm going to go over to the Texas Highway Department and buy you a 35-cent,
Blanco County map, and I will mail this to you with instructions that you take your crayons and color in areas which are significant to your upbringing, okay?
I think that'll be fun, too, you know?
You'll get a kick out of it.
And, too, when we lived... Now, when Roy was telling about this old Culberson place, well, that was... We called it the old chimney place because the house... Well, it burned down...
Soon after, well, I just don't know.
See, we moved down there in 1912.
And it must have been, it burned down about 1913 or 1914.
I don't know.
I see.
But anyway, right along in there.
How old was the house?
When was it built?
Oh, my heavens.
That old house was built in, oh, back in 18...
I guess about 1860.
Was it?
One of the earliest?
One of the very earliest houses is built in this country.
Okay.
And that was on the road to Cypress Mills.
Yes, right.
And they'd go through that way to go to dances.
My mother and Aunt Mabel and Uncle Jay would go by the old Culberson place going to a dance.
Right.
I know something I want to ask you about.
Let's go back.
I want you to do a small genealogy chart also of your family.
You know what I'm saying, the Chapman side, the Johnson side.
Because you know you've got some German roots.
I sure do, and I'm proud of them.
That means I'm proud of all of them.
told me one time, Scotch, Irish, and devil.
I really realize that.
I know that now.
Scotch, Irish, and devil.
I know that now as time goes on.
I met some Scottish friends the other day, and I know I can see it very plainly.
The Macintosh and the Macintyres and the Buttons were all Scotch.
Irish.
My grandmother was a
Her mother was a Macintyre.
And her mother was a Macintosh.
So that pretty well puts the discussion... That pretty well puts me right in there.
In the middle of it.
And, of course, the Johnsons originally were sweet.
When they came and...
When England and Norway were... Having their trouble with the North Sea and whatnot, the Johnsons went into...
England.
And soon after they landed there, they dropped the T, Johnston, and made it Johnson.
Yeah.
I see.
See, and then they came from there.
I believe their first, well, it was four brothers of them that came over together.
And one of them stopped in Boston.
right at the Plymouth Rock, you might say.
And the other one was down further on down New Jersey, one in Virginia.
And, well, my grandparents,
I am sure from what I can gather was one that stopped in Virginia.
Yeah.
And so that's and then of course they came on over into Kentucky and
You know, Grandmother Johnson was born in Russellville, Kentucky.
She was born in Russellville?
Yes, ma'am.
I've been there.
Born in Russellville, Kentucky.
How about that?
Yes, sir.
And then, well, my grandfather was born in Georgia.
Uh-huh.
And my great-grandfather Johnson was sheriff in Georgia.
Uh-huh.
Well, let's see what county it was at.
Well, I have it.
I'll put it, I'll send it to you.
Okay, good.
But anyway, he was sheriff there for years.
I don't know.
It must have been in the blood of the Johnsons to be in politics.
Yeah.
I think it was.
Because he was sheriff, and he had a son that was sheriff, and Grandpa Johnson, he was just a trail drover.
That was it, and a preacher.
Boy, he knew his Bible.
But I don't know.
I know when they came to Texas, Grandfather preached a lot in Louisiana, too.
Mm-hmm.
Mississippi, as they came through.
He was always a very religious man.
He was a Baptist up until he went into the Christian church, which is a branch of the Puritan religion.
But he preached along the way.
He came along in the covered wagon.
He was a preacher.
Yeah, so that's very interesting.
And then he went into the cattle industry right here.
Why don't you tell me about just, well, I know I can look up a lot of information, but I'd rather hear it from you.
Well, the only thing, I know that my first time grandfather came here was back in the early 50s.
And I said the early 50s.
I don't mean the early 50s.
I mean the late 50s.
And he brought that provost built the first cabin up there on the old Johnson Place.
And grandfather bought it from provost.
Uh-huh.
And who was provost?
The provost was just one of the first settlers in this part of the country.
And the Wallers were early settlers here.
The Criters, the Summys, provosts, Mays, Kletts, Kellys, Greens, Harringtons, Smiths.
That gets about all of them.
About everybody.
About everybody.
And they were all early settlers here.
And then in 1858, grandfather bought.
And we didn't have any wire fence laws at that time.
And that is another thing that you went by marks of trees.
and rocks and rivers as landmarks and boundaries for your land.
And our deed, which God bless the little old Park's heart, says to, well they kept telling
Corky rode the wagon, and they kept saying, this is Brookner property.
Well, it was not.
It was Sam Ely's property, and where the exhibit hall is was on the Sam Johnson property for grandfathers.
The only little thing, you know where the chuck wagon is?
Yes.
That side of the creek, now.
I said that side of the creek.
Uh-huh.
was Brookner's and up and where the old smokehouse, there was a straight line that went right straight out to the field.
Now that was Brookner's.
And they kept, I don't know, I can't understand why they can't look at their own deed and see that.
But anyway, they didn't.
They were just writing their own history.
Yes, they were doing their own history.
Anyway, they said Pope Johnson's barn wasn't there, but oh, it was.
And it was there when grandmother was held under the house by the Indians because grandfather has told me that story many, many times.
Why don't you tell me that story?
Well, he had gone to get some
stairs that he had bought from the Phelps's down on Miller Creek.
About what time was this?
It was in the fall of the year because they were going to make well I said fall is late summer.
Probably in September.
About this time of the year.
And he was going and he went down there to bring the stairs that he had bought from the Phelps's to
up to the old settlement house, which they call the old settlement place.
It's the Johnson House.
And he left grandmother there with Aunt Mary, who was the oldest child.
And she was a person...
that could shoot as well as any Indian and ride just as well.
That's grandmother Bunton Johnson.
Grandmother Bunton, Eliza Jane Bunton Johnson.
And she was quite a lady.
She was not a woman who talked a lot.
But when she spoke, you listened.
And what she had to say was worth it.
And I can tell you one thing.
She didn't tell you twice not to do something.
She told you once, and if you did it, there was always a reason that she used that butter paddle.
Mm-hmm.
The butter paddle.
The butter paddle.
Oh, or that old wooden spoon.
Man, why that hurt.
Okay.
I well remember that.
The butter paddle and wooden spoon.
And I didn't get but two of them.
And that was all it took.
For your grandmother.
For my grandmother.
Right.
Well, my grandfather didn't think I ever deserved anything like that.
No.
I'd have never gotten a spanking.
I'll guarantee you that.
Well, anyway, that day when the Indians came.
And the Indians came, and Grandmother crawled under the house.
Well, she was down at the spring getting water.
And we dug that spring out and made that hole of water.
Now, is that the spring that's right behind you?
Right.
Your old house there?
Old, yes.
Right down there by the exhibit center.
Right.
And that was the string that was on top of the ground.
But it had a hole dug out to get water.
But anyway, we dug that thing out to irrigate with.
Yeah, and you had the pecans.
And the pecans, yeah.
In the early 20s.
Well, grandmother's down there getting water and she looked out across the flat.
That's the reason I told you a while ago we didn't have these cedars and we didn't have all that.
Right, you had the flat grassland.
Grassland.
And she saw these Indians coming.
And she ran to the house and grabbed little Mary and right in front of that fireplace was a trap door.
Yes.
And there was a root cellar under the house, not a big old thing, but a root cellar is all it was where she put her things.
And lots of times, that's where she kept a lot of her groceries to keep the Indians from stealing them.
What kind of Indians were these?
The Comanches.
Comanches.
When she heard them coming, she grabbed little Mary and the diapers out and crawled under there and just pulled this door down.
It had an old rug in front of it.
And it didn't show to be a door or anything because the floor was pieced all the way across with lumber, but only part of it came up.
And that was because of the way it was built.
And you didn't know it was a door.
And she got down there, and she kept little Mary in.
These Indians stole so many of her wedding gifts, and all of the supplies that Grandfather had gotten from Austin to go on this cattle drive, he and Uncle Tom, and she knew that
Little Mary would cry and wake them and she tied a diaper around her mouth so that it would muffle the cry.
And she could hear the Indians taking the things out of the house.
She could hear them going through her trunk and everything.
And she heard the cattle stampede at the barn, and she knew that they were driving them off or doing something.
She couldn't tell what.
And she heard the horses when they broke out of the pen and they opened the gate.
They stole a couple of his saddle horses, and they killed a beef.

and took it and it was after night when grandfather came in and he knew that something was wrong because the cattle sat and he knew the horses was out and all out and around the place and he knew there was something wrong and he came in and he hollered Eliza Eliza where are you are you here he went back to the barn and
He called for Uncle Tom and he said, Tom, where are you?
And Tom said, I'm rounding up the stock, bringing them back to the pen.
He says, come on, we've got to find Liza.
Indians have been here.
They've killed a beef.
The horses are gone.
We've got to find Liza and Mary, little Mary.
And Uncle Tom said, well, have you looked at the house?
And he said, she's not there.
She didn't answer me.
He said, well, let's go back and
to the house and see.
He said, she might be around there and we might find her.
And so grandfather came in and he said, Eliza, and she didn't answer.
Called Eliza again.
He stomped his boot heel.
He says, Eliza Jane Button, if you're here, answer me.
And when he said Eliza Jane Button, she answered.
And he said, well, why didn't you answer me before?
She said, Sam Ely, an Indian can mimic anything, and I knew no one knew that my name was Eliza Jane but you.
And that's the reason I answered.
Oh, how about that, yeah.
And the only reason I answered was because you called me Eliza Jane Button, and that's the reason I answered.
Well, soon after that, they had the Battle of Deer Creek.
And the wounded were taken there to the house.
Well, grandmother didn't have any cotton.
Now, what year was that?
I can't remember.
I know what the Battle of Deer Creek was, but I don't have it written down, so I can't.
I can't tell you.
I can look it up.
It was in the 60s, so early part.
The Battle of Deer Creek, was that because the Phelps were murdered?
That was before.
I mean, after the Phelpses were murdered, the Phelpses were scalped first.
Yeah.
And then the Battle of Deer Creek.
Then the Battle of Deer Creek.
The Dolly Heights were killed at Round Mountain also.
Now, I'm not familiar with that.
Well, the Dolly Heights were on their way to church.
Uh-huh.
And that's Emmett Redford's great-grandfather.
Oh, really?
You bet.
Whoa, okay.
And they were, his mother was a Dolly Hyde.
A Dolly Hyde.
Yes, Emmett Redford's mother was a Dolly Hyde.
Okay, all right.
And Emmett Redford's mother taught me one year in declamations, and I won in the county, went to the district.
And I recited a poem that Daniel Webster wrote.
Oh, you did?
Mm-hmm.
Which was that?
It was that.
the nation, our nation, and he said, God grant that I shall not see a divided nation, that this curtain shall never rise again.
It's a beautiful poem, and it is so true.
You'll have to go back.
That happened first?
Yeah, before the Battle of Deer Creek.
Now, the Dolly Heights were killed and the Phelps were scalped.
Then the Battle of Deer Creek.
Then the Battle of Deer Creek.
Well, grandmother put under the cabin before any of that.
Yeah, she went under the cabin before any of all that happened.
All that happened.
This all led up to the Battle of Deer Creek.
This all led up to that.
And that's when they chased them out to Pack Saddle Mountain.
That's right.
Isn't that correct?
Yes, sir.
And you had some rangers come in on that?
Yes, sir.
And what was that about?
I remember.
Well, they just was trying to rid them out of the country.
Just chasing them out.
Just chasing them out.
That is all.
And...
Captain Ruth Perry.
And his old cabin is right up here in town.
Uh-huh.
Which one is that?
Minnie Cox has her.
Minnie Cox's house is Perry's cabin.
Cabin.
Old Ruth Perry's cabin.
You bet your bottom dollar.
I see.
Okay.
And I can't, law me alive.
You know, I tell you, whenever you stop to think about it, Uh-huh.
Uh,
When Ruth Perry came to visit, Grandfather, little folks have big ears.
And I'd sit and listen to those Indian tales.
Really?
Be scared to death and couldn't go to sleep that night.
And Grandma and Grandpa, me and I'd have to go and crawl in bed, and I'd get between them.
The Indians would get me every time he'd come.
But I'd want another story.
I'd want him to tell me another story.
And I'd sit and listen.
Tell me about your relationship to your grandfather, Johnson, and to Eliza, the time you did spend with them.
And I think you've told me about...
Uncle Jesse, too.
Oh, Uncle Jesse was the one that really played a very important part.
And I want to hear about him again.
He was whose?
He was Grandpa Johnson's brother.
Grandpa Johnson.
Tom.
Tom and Sam and Jesse were all brothers.
And Jesse was in the Civil War.
Uh-huh.
Fought for the South, of course.
So did Grandfather.
So did Uncle Tom.
Right.
All three of them.
All three of them.
Okay.
And Uncle Jesse got his leg shot off.
And you're very sensitive about that.
Yeah.
And I... You tell me about Uncle Jesse.
He seems to be one of my favorite characters, too.
He was one of the sweetest men that ever lived.
He's a man that loved nature.
And I think that's where it was really instilled in me.
We lived back behind Grandfather, up in about, oh, I guess a good mile from where Lyndon lived, back to...
three-quarter of a mile from Grandfather Johnson.
And every afternoon, it would be Uncle Jesse would go down.
And we had a field.
We lived out in the field, and the well was close to the house.
But the pasture had a lane that led down and a wooden gap that we let the cows through.
and out into the pasture, and we'd drive them in.
And it had flowers and everything in this lane.
To me, I can see the buttercups and the phlox and the hollyhocks and winecups and balimony and all kinds of beautiful flowers in this lane.
And we'd take old Dink, was the name of the old milk cow, and we'd take her down and put her out and in.
Uncle Jesse took a lot of pride and a lot of time in teaching me poetry.
Now let me tell you something.
When they say that children don't learn until they're a certain age, that's a bunch of baloney.
Because I know that I wasn't three years old and I was reciting poetry.
I believe that.
And the first...

poem that I ever learned that he ever taught me I have a secret just wait for you Wobbin and I in the sweet cherry tree because Wobbin knows it best because he built a little oh I can't tell the rest I'm afraid I'll tell it every minute and he laid the four little somethings in
Oh, the secret, I'm afraid I'll fail.
And I can remember reciting that for Uncle Jesse just as well as anything.
He told me why the robins laid four eggs, why the doves only had two, why the dove nest was so poorly built.
That all stemmed back from the Bible and the history of time.
This had nothing to do with, yet they scrapped from the ark.
Oh, is that so?
Those things.
And then there was, he'd teach me to sing, I'll lay away a suit of gray to wear to the Union blue.
I don't know.
I cherished those memories.
I only wish I had listened and paid a little bit more attention, but I always had something else to do.
He would tell me why the flowers had different colors, what made them bloom when they did, why the wine cup was called a wine cup, why the buttercup was called a buttercup.
They don't call it buttercup anywhere but in Texas, I don't think.
They call it the scarlet columbine and things like that.
But we call it buttercup.
And he'd pull the buttercup off and stick it to my nose and all that yellow pollen would be around.
He'd say, got butter on your nose?
Just tickle me to death.
And those are things that
I remember so well with Uncle Jesse.
And he took time to swing me.
And I'd say, swing me high.
And he would swing me high.
And he would sing that old spiritual, swing low sweet chariot.
For some reason, the Johnsons all liked to sing.
And they all liked music.
And he could really sing.
And could he play the, what did they call it?
French harp, juicer.
No, the juice harp is something else.
You flip it, but you can't.
No, this is the harmonica.
That's what he, and he could play that.
And man, it was something else.
But Uncle Jesse was quite a character, and he told me lots about the battles.
He did.
And how he...
about getting his leg shot off.
Do you remember that?

Yes, and he was taken in in a wagon, and he was covered up with a wagon sheet that they had and a bunch of provisions that were left behind, just throwed on top of him to keep the enemy from finding that he was

wound it in there and he was taking something i believe he said 20 miles to chattanooga to be to have this to the hospital a hospital to have that leg finished amputating he said it was just barely hanging and he asked someone to cut it off and they wouldn't but they did
tie uh well he said they cut a part of his shirt tail and tied it in string to put around as a tourniquet around that leg to keep him from bleeding to death from his own shirt and he was quite
He must have been in a mighty bad shape when he got there.
And from what he told me, tell about having nothing to eat but hard tack.
And of course, I didn't know what hard tack was.
One day my mother made a failure.
a complete failure in her biscuits, and he called it heart attack.
And I can remember that.
It was awful.
It was so hard.
She forgot to put the grease in it, she told me.
And so that...
Didn't you tell me he taught you how to count?
Oh, my goodness.
You have to tell me that story.
I love that story.
About the bedpost?
I love that one.
I have forgotten.
Cut that thing off.
See if I can remember.
I forget every time.
This bed that Uncle Jesse had was a four-poster bed, and it had been cut in rings like around it.
It was made out of black walnut.
And I believe, if I'm not badly mistaken, and I don't think I am, Dr.
Perry at Fredericksburg has that in that old two-story house.
And he bought it from Oriole.
And Uncle Jesse, it was his, given to Aunt Kate.
Aunt Kate was Oriole's mother, and so I'm sure that that's where that bed is.
But anyway, I learned to count.
I would get up, but never could I. I could get up to five, and I'd forget what six was every time.
So one day he told me, he said, six, remember you're sick.
You're a sick little girl when you get there.
You're going to be sick because I'm going to pat you if you don't get over it.
Well, I got there, and I said, I'm sick.
And he said, no, you're six.
All right, that's how I learned six.
And so then we got on, and I could count to 10.
And then from 10, he'd say, 10 and one more.
And he'd hold up two fingers.
And then I'd have to count the next bedpost.
And that was the way it rings around it.
Well, this bedpost had 10 on it.
And then it'd be 10 and one would be 11.
And I learned how to write those just because he'd say, what's the next one now?
It was a two, wasn't it?
Well, you've got the 10 over here.
You've got to put that one down.
And then put your two down.
And you've got your 10 over here, and you're just adding on to it.
Now, you'll remember that, he'd say.
You've already got your 10.
You're just adding one more to it, or you're adding two more to it.
It's 10 and 2.
10 and 3.
Well, that's 13.
And that's how I was taught to count the bedpost circles.
10 and 3.
And they say today you have modern math.
Uh-uh.
It's been here always.
Right.
Let me think of some more things.
I remember in the letter that you wrote me about when you were born, because you're the first grandchild.
I was the first granddaughter born in the Johnson family and the first grandchild born in the Chapman family.
Tom Martin was the oldest grandson born.
in the Johnson family.
He was several years older, I guess, 12 years older than I was.
That was Mary's husband?
That was Frank.
I mean, Frank.
Okay.
I need to get the children straight.
Eliza and Sam had how many children?
Nine.
Nine.
Aunt Mary was the oldest, and she died.
She was a music teacher, and she married a walling, and she went west.
Well, she had TB.
And she went to El Paso, and there's where she died.
Then Aunt Frank married Clarence Martin, was the second one.
And then Aunt Lucy married Sterling Price from Blanco.
Then Aunt Ava...
married John Harvey Bright.
She was a school teacher, and she was teaching at Granbury, taught at Granbury.
And then she taught at Beaumont, and there is where she met Uncle John Harvey and married him.
Well, and she taught at Port Arthur also.
But she was really... Well, in 1905, when they had the...
Normal Institute from St. Marcus over here at Brown Mountain.
She made the highest average of anyone in her class.
And that was in what year?
Mm-hmm.
A long time ago.
Yeah, but I know where that building is.
Yes, you know where the building is, and that's a landmark in the county.
And I have...
It should be represented by Stan Mark somehow.
Somehow.
They should have a... Well, I don't know...
They've changed hands so many times.
That's another institute that at one time it was a progressive, but seems to me like that politics or something's happened.
I don't know what's happened to it, but it's not the same old school it used to be.
Listen, after Ava, who was the next child?
After Aunt Ava came Sam.
And then I believe Uncle Sam, and then my daddy, then Aunt Kate, then Uncle George.
Then Aunt Jessie.
And Aunt Jessie was the only one living when Lyndon was president.
Oh, really?
That's the picture that we had made in Air Force One.
She and I were the only Johnson attending the inauguration.
I was the oldest grandchild, and she was the only one living.
And she was the only aunt.
And he had our picture made while I'm sitting.
That's beautiful, yeah.
If you well can see, sitting in his lap.
We'll have to use that picture, too.
That's a nice photograph of all of you.
But they couldn't understand why.
I said, if you'll just look back at all the pictures, I'm just always as close to him as I can be.
And that one, sitting in his lap.
Yeah, for sure.
Yeah.
So that was the family.
The picture hanging in the boyhood home of us in 1916, I'm holding Lennon's little sister.
Which one that was?
That was Lucia.
Lucia.
She was born in 1916.
I'm holding her.
So what year were you born?
What day?
What hour?
Well, the day and hour...
I was born in 1905 at 6 o'clock in the afternoon, the hottest day my mother said it could ever be.
In the month of?
August.
August.
The 2nd.
The 2nd.
I'm a Leo.
I get along well with Leos, okay.
I'm a Leo.
Yes.
Well, grandfather didn't go up the river hollering that a Florence Nightingale was being born or anything like that.
But I can well remember
He said, well, I have a little queen now.
I was called his little queen in Calico.
Which, that was very true.
I was treated like a little queen, as far as he's concerned.
I did no wrong.
The girls with grandfather did no wrong.
The boys did.
The girls did.
But the girls didn't.
So you and Margaret were spoiled?
Very much so.
I was three years old.
My grandfather had bought me a horse and saddle.
When you were three?
When I was three.
That's something very important because the early age that you were taught to ride
My goodness in life.
Think about a child three years old riding a mile after mail and crossing a river.
Would your parents let you do that today?
No, but it was necessary for survival that even the youngest children in a county like this, an isolated community, know that sort of thing.
Is that right?
You mighty well believe.
And we knew to ride.
We knew how to ride.
Why, I can remember that grandfather gave me, and my saddle was made, it had a great big horn, what we called a Mexican saddle horn.
He told me, he said, if you have to grab a hold of something, sister, you can't hold on to that horn.
Grab that string on the side.
I know what string you mean, right?
So I never was taught to hold on to a saddle.
That wasn't my cup of tea.
Right.
From little.
I have a pair of spurs that my grandmother gave me, engraved Eliza on.
She has, and I gave them to the park thinking they'd appreciate them and they'd put them up, and they've never been put out.
So I don't know where they are.
They're a lot.
They're cataloged to uselessness.
I guess they are cataloged to uselessness.
Right.
I didn't have a granddaughter.
I mean, at that time, I mean, well, Debbie, I could have given them to her.
I have one.
I gave her.
I have one left.
I couldn't find it, but.
In moving, never having moved in 58 years, in moving this time, I found it.
So I've got one.
I'll give it to Debbie.
I didn't give her the pair.
I just had the one when I gave it to the partner.
I would say another question here.
You learned how to survive in a man's world as well as in a woman's world.
I sure did.
You had no choice.
Your mother, of course, would have been in the same tradition because pioneer women had no choice but to survive in an equal world with their men.
That was another thing Uncle Taxi taught me to do.
What was this?
It was every evening we'd go down this trail, we had shoemake.
that grew out around.
And the life of a shoemake tree is quite short.
And we'd go over and we'd break off just so much to start our fire with the next morning.
And from a little child, I have been taking in kindling and things to start a fire with in the morning.
And let me tell you something.
The old folks didn't let their fire die out.
Uh-huh.
We didn't have matches.
So you kept that fire going all the time.
You kept that fire going all the time.
And you'd bank it in the summertime.
You'd bank it at night, cover it up with ashes so you'd have a coal to start with the next morning.
Because your flame is what kept you cooking.
That's right.
Laundry and all these things.
Everything.
That's right.
